
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `hostid` yek shomareye shenasayiye unik (unique identifier) baraye systeme shoma chap mikonad. In shomare baraye license-ha va barname-haye khasi ke be yek shenaseye masnoo'i (hardware identifier) niaz darand, estefade mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `hostid`  -->  💻 Chap kardane shenaseye host be shekle hexadecimal.
    🔹 `hostid --help` -->  ℹ️ Namayeshe rahnamaye dastoor.
    🔹 `hostid --version` -->  📦 Namayeshe version-e barnameye `hostid`.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ hostid

    🔹 Chap kardane shenaseye host. Misali az khروجی: 5a2f9b8e

    $ hostid --version

    🔹 Namayeshe version-e dastoor `hostid`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ hostid
    5a2f9b8e

    🔹 Dastoor `hostid` faghat yek shomare chap mikonad. In shomare baraye har system unik ast va baraye shenasayiye aan system dar license-ha va nagarm افزارها estefade mishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `hostid` command prints the numeric identifier (hostid) for the current system. This number is often used for software licensing or other applications that require a hardware identifier.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `hostid`  -->  💻 Prints the host identifier as a hexadecimal number.
    🔹 `hostid --help` -->  ℹ️ Displays help information about the command.
    🔹 `hostid --version` -->  📦 Displays the version of the `hostid` utility.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ hostid

    🔹 Prints the host identifier. Example output: 5a2f9b8e

    $ hostid --version

    🔹 Displays the version of the `hostid` command.

✅ **Simple Example & Explanation:**

    $ hostid
    5a2f9b8e

    🔹 The `hostid` command simply prints a number. This number is unique to the system and is used to identify it for licensing or other software purposes.
